      <h1>What Is SDE? How to Calculate Seller's Discretionary Earnings</h1>
      <div class="guide-meta">
        <span>By {{ site.author.name }}</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>Updated {{ site.dataLastModified }}</span>
        <span>·</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <section class="guide-body">

      <p>
        If you are preparing to sell your business, or simply trying to understand what it is worth,
        you will encounter the term SDE - Seller's Discretionary Earnings - within the first ten minutes
        of any conversation with a broker or buyer. SDE is the number that almost everything in a
        Main Street business sale is built on: the valuation multiple, the financing terms, and the
        final purchase price.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most business owners know their revenue. Fewer know their net profit. Almost none know their SDE  -
        which is consistently higher than net profit, and the number buyers actually use.
      </p>

      <h2>The SDE Definition</h2>
      <p>
        SDE is the total annual financial benefit a full-time owner-operator receives from owning the
        business. It answers the question: if a buyer purchased this business and worked in it full-time,
        how much money would they take home per year?
      </p>
      <p>
        The formula is:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <p><strong>SDE = Net Profit + Owner Salary + Owner Benefits + Personal Add-Backs + Non-Cash Charges</strong></p>
      </div>

      <h2>What Gets Added Back to Net Profit</h2>
      <p>
        The add-back process is where SDE differs from every other earnings metric. You are reconstructing
        the income statement to reflect what a new owner would actually earn - stripping out expenses that
        are specific to you, non-recurring, or accounting choices rather than real cash outflows.
      </p>

      <h3>1. Owner's Salary and Compensation</h3>
      <p>
        If you pay yourself a salary through the business - even a minimal one - it is added back to net profit.
        The buyer will pay themselves a salary from the SDE after purchase, so including your salary in the
        expenses would double-count it. Add back the full amount shown on your W-2 or K-1 that came from the
        business.
      </p>

      <h3>2. Owner's Benefits</h3>
      <p>
        Health insurance, dental, life insurance premiums, and retirement contributions (SEP-IRA, SIMPLE IRA,
        Solo 401k) paid by the business for the owner's benefit are added back. These are owner-specific costs
        that would not necessarily continue at the same level under new ownership.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Personal Expenses Run Through the Business</h3>
      <p>
        Personal vehicle payments or mileage reimbursements, personal travel, meals and entertainment beyond
        ordinary business activity, personal cell phone bills, and similar expenses are added back if they
        are personal in nature rather than operationally required. These must be documented - buyers will
        request bank statements and credit card statements during diligence.
      </p>

      <h3>4. One-Time and Non-Recurring Expenses</h3>
      <p>
        A lawsuit settlement, a one-time equipment write-off, the cost of relocating the business, or any
        other expense that will not recur under new ownership is added back. These reduce net profit but do
        not reflect the ongoing earnings power of the business. Buyers and their lenders are sophisticated  -
        they look for add-backs that are genuinely non-recurring, not a pattern of "one-time" events every year.
      </p>

      <h3>5. Depreciation and Amortization</h3>
      <p>
        Depreciation is a non-cash accounting charge - no cash leaves the business when depreciation is
        recorded. Add it back. Amortization of goodwill or intangibles is similarly non-cash. Both reduce
        reported net profit without affecting actual cash available to the owner.
      </p>

      <h3>6. Interest Expense</h3>
      <p>
        Interest paid on business loans is added back because the buyer may not assume the debt, or may
        refinance at different terms. The earnings power of the business should be evaluated independent
        of its current debt structure.
      </p>

      <h2>A Worked Example</h2>
      <p>
        Imagine you own a residential cleaning business. Your tax return shows:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>Revenue: $620,000</li>
        <li>Net profit after all expenses: $42,000</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        That $42,000 net profit is what most owners quote when asked what their business makes.
        But the SDE picture looks different:
      </p>
      <div class="formula-block">
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Net Profit (from tax return)</th><td>$42,000</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Owner salary (W-2)</th><td>+$85,000</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Owner health insurance (business-paid)</th><td>+$14,400</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Personal vehicle (business-expensed)</th><td>+$7,200</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Depreciation on equipment</th><td>+$8,500</td></tr>
            <tr><th>One-time legal expense</th><td>+$6,000</td></tr>
            <tr><th><strong>SDE</strong></th><td><strong>$163,100</strong></td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p>
        At a <a href="/valuation/cleaning-businesses/">cleaning business median multiple of 2.44×</a>,
        an SDE of $163,100 produces a valuation of approximately $397,964 - not the $102,000 a buyer
        would derive from multiplying net profit by the same multiple. The difference between knowing
        your SDE and not knowing it is the difference between a fair sale and a deeply underpriced one.
      </p>

      <h2>Why Buyers and Lenders Use SDE</h2>
      <p>
        SBA lenders - the most common financing source for Main Street acquisitions - underwrite the loan
        based on whether the business's SDE can cover the debt service. A business with $163,100 SDE and
        a $400,000 purchase price at 10% interest over 10 years generates annual debt service of
        approximately $63,400, leaving a meaningful coverage ratio. The SBA requires a debt service
        coverage ratio (DSCR) of 1.25× - meaning SDE must be at least 1.25× the annual debt payments.
        Knowing your SDE before entering negotiations tells you whether your business will qualify for SBA
        financing at a given price, which directly affects who can buy it.
      </p>

      <h2>Common SDE Calculation Mistakes</h2>

      <h3>Adding Back Expenses That Will Continue</h3>
      <p>
        Not every owner expense is a legitimate add-back. A vehicle that is genuinely necessary for business
        operations - a plumber's work truck, a landscaper's trailer - is not a personal add-back. If the
        new owner will need the vehicle to operate the business, it stays as an expense. Only add back
        what a buyer would not incur.
      </p>

      <h3>Counting Revenue Twice</h3>
      <p>
        Some owners add back cash income that was never reported on the tax return. Buyers cannot finance
        unreported income - SBA lenders will not count it, and most buyers won't pay for it either.
        Consistent tax reporting is the foundation of a defensible SDE.
      </p>

      <h3>Using Peak-Year SDE</h3>
      <p>
        Buyers and brokers typically use a trailing-twelve-month or three-year weighted-average SDE,
        not a single peak year. A business that had $300,000 SDE in 2022, $180,000 in 2023, and
        $200,000 in 2024 will not be valued on the $300,000. The trend matters - which is one reason
        the <a href="/">valuation calculator</a> includes revenue trend as an input.
      </p>

      <h2>SDE vs. EBITDA: When Each Applies</h2>
      <p>
        SDE is the standard for Main Street businesses - roughly those with revenue under $5M or SDE under
        $1M. Above those thresholds, buyers shift to EBITDA multiples. The primary difference: SDE adds back
        the owner's full compensation; EBITDA adds back only a market-rate management salary.
      </p>
      <p>
        For a detailed comparison with worked examples for both metrics, see
        <a href="/guides/ebitda-vs-sde/">EBITDA vs SDE: Which Matters When Selling Your Business</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With Your SDE Number</h2>
      <p>
        Once you have calculated your SDE, you can:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Apply an industry-specific multiple using the
          <a href="/">free valuation calculator</a>
          - select your industry, enter your SDE and revenue, and get an adjusted range in under two minutes
        </li>
        <li>
          Use the multiple range for your industry to understand the ceiling and floor of realistic offers
        </li>
        <li>
          Compare your SDE margin (SDE ÷ Revenue) to industry benchmarks - low margins often indicate
          operational inefficiencies that buyers will price in
        </li>
        <li>
          Identify add-back documentation you need to compile before going to market - every add-back
          requires a paper trail
        </li>
      </ul>

